# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cricket-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The **1912 Triangular Tournament** was a Test cricket competition played between Australia, England and South Africa, the only Test-playing nations at the time.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The ultimate winners of the tournament were England, with four wins in their six matches, but the tournament was deemed a failure, with disappointing crowds and uncompetitive cricket, caused in part by a weakened Australia team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was the first tournament in Test history to be played between more than two nations.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] It was the only such tournament until the Asian Test Championships of 1998–99 and 2001–02, and the ICC World Test Championship which began in 2019.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a competition involving all three of the nations then playing Test cricket (Australia, England and South Africa) was proposed at the first meeting of the Imperial Cricket Conference in July 1909.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The original proposal was for a tournament to be held every four years, with the first hosted by England in 1912.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] For a variety of reasons, the tournament was not a success.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The summer was one of the wettest since records began in 1766: rainfall in the three months of June, July and August was more than twice the seasonal average, and August, 1912, was the coolest, dullest and wettest August of the 20th century.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] At that time, pitches were not covered to protect them against rain, so the batsmen were at a distinct disadvantage on the proverbial sticky wicket.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] These problems were exacerbated since Tests in England were in those days played over three days rather than the five days that is now usual.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] In addition, disputes between the players and management in Australia meant that six leading Australian players refused to tour whilst medical duties meant “Ranji” Hordern, easily Australia’s best bowler in the 1911–12 Ashes series, could not tour either.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] These setbacks severely weakened a team that had otherwise been level with England in recent Ashes series.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The leg spin and googly bowlers in the South African team were very effective on the matting pitches then in use in South Africa, but were less deadly on English grass pitches.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] As a result, England dominated, winning four of their six matches and drawing the other two.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was so unsuccessful that it has never been repeated.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a tournament of international cricket matches between more than two countries was not repeated, outside of regional tournaments in East Africa and the West Indies, until the invention of One Day International cricket and the first Women's Cricket World Cup in 1973.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] The only other Test cricket tournaments in history were the Asian Test Championships played in 1998–99 and 2001–02, which were also not great successes, until the ICC World Test Championship began in 2019.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1912-triangular-tournament] Perhaps the most notable incident of the series was Australian bowler Jimmy Matthews taking two hat-tricks in the same Test match, one in each innings of the opening match against South Africa, the only time a bowler has taken two hat-tricks in the same Test.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] 1962 was the 63rd season of County Championship cricket in England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] It was also the last season to feature the venerable Gentlemen v Players fixture: as a result of the distinction between amateurs ("Gentlemen") and professionals ("Players") being abolished following the end of the season, all first-class cricketers became nominally professional (or "Players").
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] Yorkshire won the County Championship, and England easily defeated an inexperienced Pakistan team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] The first was at Lord's from Wednesday, 18 July to Friday, 20 July and was drawn.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] The teams were captained by Ted Dexter (Gentlemen) and Fred Trueman (Players).
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] The second match was played at the North Marine Road Ground, Scarborough from Saturday, 8 September to Tuesday, 11 September.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] Mike Smith captained the Gentlemen in this match and Trueman again led the Players.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] The match at Scarborough was also the final edition of the fixture which began in 1806: from the start of the 1963 season, amateur status in first-class cricket was abolished.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] Thus, all players thenceforward had equal status as cricketers and were nominally professionals or "Players", with the "Gentlemen" ceasing to exist.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] There is a team photograph of the Gentlemen XI in the Lord's match.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] They were: (*back row, l to r*) Roger Prideaux, David Pithey, Ossie Wheatley, Tony Lewis, Alan Smith (wk), Edward Craig; (*front row, l to r*) Bob Barber, Trevor Bailey, Ted Dexter (captain), David Sheppard, Mike Smith.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] In its 1963 edition, *Wisden Cricketers' Almanack* announced that its five cricketers of the 1962 season were Don Kenyon, Mushtaq Mohammad, Peter Parfitt, Phil Sharpe and Fred Titmus.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1962-english-cricket-season] As a rule, though it has occasionally been broken, *Wisden* never selects a player more than once.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] 1963 was the 64th season of County Championship cricket in England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] Limited overs cricket began with the first edition of the knockout competition that was originally called the Gillette Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] The highlight of the season was a memorable Test series between England and West Indies which the tourists won 3–1.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] Yorkshire won their second consecutive championship title.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] Off the field, the year saw the publication of the hundredth edition of Wisden Cricketers' Almanack, as well as the deaths of two cricketing knights, Sir Jack Hobbs and Sir Pelham Warner.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] There was a memorable series between England and West Indies.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] The tourists won 3–1 with one match drawn.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] The Lord's Test had one of the most exciting finishes ever and all four results were possible with two balls to be bowled: it ended as a draw with England five runs behind and their last pair batting.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] Colin Cowdrey had gone in as number 11 with a broken arm, but did not have to face a ball.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] As a result of the great success of this series, England's future home Test programme was revised so that West Indies could return in 1966, much earlier than originally planned.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1963-english-cricket-season] This was done by introducing "twin tours", in which two countries would each play three Tests against England in the course of a season.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] The **1969 English cricket season** was the 70th in which the County Championship had been an official competition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] The *Sunday League* (now the National League) began, sponsored by the John Player tobacco company.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] All matches were played on Sundays with each of the 17 first-class counties playing each other once.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] One match each Sunday was televised by the BBC and the idea was a commercial success, though it had its critics among cricket's "traditional" supporters.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] One effect of the Sunday League was a reduction in the number of matches played by each team in the County Championship from 28 to 24.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] England defeated both West Indies and New Zealand in Test series.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] England had a very strong team captained by Ray Illingworth.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] Other notable England players included John Snow, Geoff Boycott, John Edrich, Alan Knott and Derek Underwood.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] John Hampshire scored a century on his Test debut versus West Indies at Lord's.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] John Edrich topped the averages with 2238 runs at 69.93.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] Other leading batsmen were Basil Butcher, Mushtaq Mohammed and Barry Richards, who all averaged over 50.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] Alan Ward was the leading bowler, with an average of 14.82, but he took only 69 wickets, whereas four bowlers took over 100 wickets each.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1969-english-cricket-season] These were Mike Procter, Derek Underwood, Tom Cartwright and Don Wilson, who all averaged less than 17.50.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1975 Cricket World Cup Final** was a One Day International cricket match played at Lord's, London, on 21 June 1975 to determine the winner of the 1975 Cricket World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] It was the second time that the West Indies and Australia had met in the tournament, after playing against each other in the group stage.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The West Indies won the match by 17 runs to claim their first title.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] West Indies qualified for the knockouts with a first-place finish in Group B.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The team won all three of their matches against Australia, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then in the semi-final against New Zealand, the opposition opened brilliantly, but when Glenn Turner fell, the wickets tumbled the West Indies scored the required 158 to reach the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia made it through to the knockouts in second place with their only loss being against the West Indies.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] But they did defeat Pakistan and Sri Lanka to take on England in the semi-final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Gary Gilmour took six wickets in the English innings to help them through to the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first final was played on 21 June (Midsummer of that year), a sunny day, in front of a capacity crowd of 26,765.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won the toss and invited the West Indies to bat, hoping to make use of ideal bowling conditions.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first moment of drama came when opener Roy Fredericks was dismissed hit wicket; he hooked a bouncer from Dennis Lillee for six, but in his follow-through lost his balance and knocked the bails off the stumps.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were on top at 50/3 when West Indian captain Clive Lloyd came to the crease in partnership with veteran Rohan Kanhai.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair swung the match in the West Indies' favour by putting on 149 for the fourth wicket.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai played the anchor role – not scoring for 11 overs – while Lloyd took on the Australian bowling attack, surviving a dropped catch on 26 to score a century off 82 balls with 12 fours and two sixes, being dismissed shortly afterwards for 102.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai, in what would be his farewell from international cricket, scored an invaluable 55.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Solid contributions from Keith Boyce and Bernard Julien helped the West Indies close their innings at 291/8.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Burly left-arm seamer Gary Gilmour was the pick of the Australian bowlers with 5/48, backing up his strong semi-final performance.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The Australian run chase began steadily: at the 20-over mark, they were 80/1 with Alan Turner and captain Ian Chappell taking advantage of an easy pitch and fast outfield.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then Viv Richards, who had failed with the bat, left his mark on the match with the next three run-outs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] First he swooped in and dismissed Turner with a direct hit from close range, then Greg Chappell was also out with a direct hit after a slight misfield.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Doug Walters came in and helped his captain steady the ship.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were at 162/3 with 21 overs remaining when Chappell, facing his opposing captain, pushed a ball to the left of mid-wicket and started off for a run.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] He hesitated initially when he saw Richards approaching but started off again after Richards fumbled the ball, only to be caught short of the crease by Richards' lightning recovery and return to Lloyd at the bowler's end.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] In each situation, the batsmen probably would have made the run had they not hesitated.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When Lillee joined Jeff Thomson as last man in, Australia required 59 runs to win off seven overs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The duo kept the game alive, putting on an unlikely last-wicket stand.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] With three overs remaining Lillee hit a no-ball to Fredericks at extra cover off Vanburn Holder and the crowd rushed on to the field oblivious to the umpire's call.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Amid the chaos, Fredericks attempted a run-out but missed and the ball disappeared into the crowd.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Lillee and Thomson kept running between the wickets until the crowd was dispersed.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When play was resumed, the umpires decided to give Australia two runs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] After protest from Thomson, they awarded three runs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The match finally ended three balls later after Thomson had run a leg bye and Lillee scored a single.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The final wicket fell with Thomson swinging wildly and missing.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Having not realised the wicket-keeper had held the ball Thomson set off for a run, attempted to return after recognising his mistake but not before Murray knocked the bails off with a well-aimed underarm throw with his gloves on for a run-out.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The game ended at 8:43 pm after nearly 10 hours play.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Another pitch invasion ensued as the players and umpires ran for safety, with Thomson having his cricket pads stolen, Boyce losing his shoes and umpire Bird having his hat taken.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Bird later said that he came across the stolen hat being worn by a bus conductor in London a year after the event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When he asked about it, he was told by the conductor, who did not recognise Bird, that he'd "won the race" by sprinting onto the field at the final to take it.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The **ICC Men's Cricket World Cup** is a quadrennial world cup for cricket in One Day International (ODI) format, organised by the International Cricket Council (ICC).
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The tournament is one of the world's most viewed sporting events and considered the flagship event of the international cricket calendar by the ICC.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first Cricket World Cup was organised in England in June 1975, with the first ODI cricket match having been played only four years earlier.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] However, a separate Women's Cricket World Cup had been held two years before the first men's tournament, and a tournament involving multiple international teams had been held as early as 1912, when a triangular tournament of Test matches was played between Australia, England and South Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first three World Cups were held in England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] From the 1987 tournament onwards, hosting has been shared between countries under an unofficial rotation system, with 14 ICC members having hosted at least one match in the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The current format involves a qualification phase, which takes place over the preceding three years, to determine which teams qualify for the tournament phase.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the tournament phase, 10 teams, including the automatically qualifying host nation, compete for the title at venues within the host nation over about a month.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the 2027 World Cup, the format will be changed to accommodate an expanded 14-team final competition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] A total of twenty teams have competed in the 13 editions of the tournament, with ten teams competing in the recent 2023 tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia has won the tournament six times, India and West Indies twice each, while Pakistan, Sri Lanka and England have won it once each.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The best performance by a non-full-member team came when Kenya made the semi-finals of the 2003 tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia are the current champions after winning the 2023 World Cup in India.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The subsequent 2027 World Cup will be held jointly in South Africa, Zimbabwe and Namibia.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first international cricket match was played between Canada and the United States, on 24 and 25 September 1844.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] However, the first credited Test match was played in 1877 between Australia and England, and the two teams competed regularly for The Ashes in subsequent years.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] South Africa was admitted to Test status in 1889.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Representative cricket teams were selected to tour each other, resulting in bilateral competition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Cricket was also included as an Olympic sport at the 1900 Paris Games, where Great Britain defeated France to win the gold medal.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] This was the only appearance of cricket at the Summer Olympics.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament, a Test cricket tournament played in England between all three Test-playing nations at the time: England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The event was not a success: the summer was exceptionally wet, making play difficult on damp uncovered pitches, and crowd attendances were poor, attributed to a "surfeit of cricket".
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Since then, international Test cricket has generally been organised as bilateral series: a multilateral Test tournament was not organised again until the triangular Asian Test Championship in 1999.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of nations playing Test cricket increased gradually over time, with the addition of West Indies in 1928, New Zealand in 1930, India in 1932, and Pakistan in 1952.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] However, international cricket continued to be played as bilateral Test matches over three, four or five days.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the early 1960s, English county cricket teams began playing a shortened version of cricket which only lasted for one day.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Starting in 1962 with a four-team knockout competition known as the Midlands Knock-Out Cup, and continuing with the inaugural Gillette Cup in 1963, one-day cricket grew in popularity in England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] A national Sunday League was formed in 1969.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first One-Day International match was played on the fifth day of a rain-aborted Test match between England and Australia at Melbourne in 1971, to fill the time available and as compensation for the frustrated crowd.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] It was a forty over game with eight balls per over, and saw Australia win by 5 wickets.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The success and popularity of the domestic one-day competitions in England and other parts of the world, as well as the early One-Day Internationals, prompted the ICC to consider organizing a Cricket World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The inaugural Cricket World Cup was hosted in 1975 by England, the only nation able to put forward the resources to stage an event of such magnitude at the time.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first three tournaments were held in England and officially known as the Prudential Cup after the sponsors Prudential plc.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The matches consisted of 60 six-ball overs per team, played during daytime in the traditional form, with the players wearing cricket whites and using red cricket balls.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Eight teams participated in the first tournament: Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, and the West Indies (the six Test nations at the time), together with Sri Lanka and a composite team from East Africa.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] One notable omission was South Africa, who were banned from international cricket due to apartheid.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The tournament was won by the West Indies, who defeated Australia by 17 runs in the final at Lord's.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Roy Fredricks of West Indies was the first batsmen who got hit-wicket in ODI during the 1975 World Cup final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 1979 World Cup saw the introduction of the ICC Trophy competition to select non-Test playing teams for the World Cup, with Sri Lanka and Canada qualifying.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The West Indies won a second consecutive World Cup tournament, defeating the hosts England by 92 runs in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] At a meeting which followed the World Cup, the International Cricket Conference agreed to make the competition a quadrennial event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 1983 event was hosted by England for a third consecutive time.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] By this stage, Sri Lanka had become a Test-playing nation, and Zimbabwe qualified through the ICC Trophy.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] A fielding circle was introduced, 30 yards (27 m) away from the stumps.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Four fieldsmen needed to be inside it at all times.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The teams faced each other twice, before moving into the knock-outs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India was crowned champions after upsetting the West Indies by 43 runs in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India and Pakistan jointly hosted the 1987 tournament, the first time that the competition was held outside England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The games were reduced from 60 to 50 overs per innings, the current standard, because of the shorter daylight hours in the Indian subcontinent compared with England's summer.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia won the championship by defeating England by 7 runs in the final, the closest margin in the World Cup final until the 2019 edition between England and New Zealand.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 1992 World Cup, held in Australia and New Zealand, introduced many changes to the game, such as coloured clothing, white balls, day/night matches, and a change to the fielding restriction rules.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The South African cricket team participated in the event for the first time, following the fall of the apartheid regime and the end of the international sports boycott.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Pakistan overcame a dismal start in the tournament to eventually defeat England by 22 runs in the final and emerge as winners.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 1996 championship was held in the Indian subcontinent for a second time, with the inclusion of Sri Lanka as host for some of its group stage matches.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the semi-final, Sri Lanka, heading towards a crushing victory over India at Eden Gardens after the hosts lost eight wickets while scoring 120 runs in pursuit of 252, were awarded victory by default after crowd unrest broke out in protest against the Indian performance.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Sri Lanka went on to win their maiden championship by defeating Australia by seven wickets in the final at Lahore.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In 1999, the event was hosted by England, with some matches also being held in Scotland, Ireland, Wales and the Netherlands.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia qualified for the semi-finals after reaching their target in their Super 6 match against South Africa off the final over of the match.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] They then proceeded to the final with a tied match in the semi-final also against South Africa where a mix-up between South African batsmen Lance Klusener and Allan Donald saw Donald drop his bat and stranded mid-pitch to be run out.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the final, Australia dismissed Pakistan for 132 and then reached the target in less than 20 overs and with eight wickets in hand.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] South Africa, Zimbabwe and Kenya hosted the 2003 World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of teams participating in the event increased from twelve to fourteen.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Kenya's victories over Sri Lanka and Zimbabwe, among others – and a forfeit by the New Zealand team, which refused to play in Kenya because of security concerns – enabled Kenya to reach the semi-finals, the best result by an associate.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the final, Australia made 359 runs for the loss of two wickets, the largest ever total in a final, defeating India by 125 runs.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In 2007, the tournament was hosted by the West Indies and expanded to sixteen teams.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Following Pakistan's upset loss to World Cup debutants Ireland in the group stage, Pakistani coach Bob Woolmer was found dead in his hotel room.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Jamaican police had initially launched a murder investigation into Woolmer's death but later confirmed that he died of heart failure.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia defeated Sri Lanka in the final by 53 runs (D/L) in farcical light conditions, and extended their undefeated run in the World Cup to 29 matches and winning three straight championships.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India, Sri Lanka and Bangladesh together hosted the 2011 World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Pakistan was stripped of its hosting rights following the terrorist attack on the Sri Lankan cricket team in 2009, with the games originally scheduled for Pakistan redistributed to the other host countries.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of teams participating in the World Cup was reduced to fourteen.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia lost their final group stage match against Pakistan on 19 March 2011, ending an unbeaten streak of 35 World Cup matches, which had begun on 23 May 1999.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India won their second World Cup title by beating Sri Lanka by 6 wickets in the final at Wankhede Stadium in Mumbai, where the Indian captain M.S.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Dhoni along with the spinning all-rounder Yuvraj Singh chased 275 with notable performances from Gautam Gambhir and Virat Kohli, making India the first country to win the World Cup at home.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] This was also the first time that two Asian countries faced each other in a World Cup Final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia and New Zealand jointly hosted the 2015 World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of participants remained at fourteen.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Ireland was the most successful Associate nation with a total of three wins in the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] New Zealand beat South Africa in a thrilling first semi-final to qualify for their maiden World Cup final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia defeated New Zealand by seven wickets in the final at Melbourne to lift the World Cup for the fifth time.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 2019 World Cup was hosted by England and Wales.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of participants was reduced to 10.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] New Zealand defeated India in the first semi-final, which was pushed over to the reserve day due to rain.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] England defeated the defending champions, Australia, in the second semi-final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Neither finalist had previously won the World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the final, the scores were tied at 241 after 50 overs and the match went to a super over, after which the scores were again tied at 15.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The World Cup was won by England, whose boundary count was greater than New Zealand's.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 2023 Cricket World Cup was hosted by India.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of teams in the tournament remained at 10, including the Netherlands, which returned to the tournament after a 12-year absence and excluding the inaugural and two-time champions the West Indies; they failed to qualify for the World Cup for the first time in history.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India were unbeaten in the group stage, as they won all of their matches and defeated New Zealand to advance to the final; Australia lost twice during the group stage before rebounding and going on an eight-game winning streak, including a defeat of South Africa in the semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Afghanistan had their most successful World Cup, with four wins during the group stage, including over defending champions England and former champions Pakistan; they also came close to defeating Australia before Glenn Maxwell's double century steered the Aussies to victory.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the final, Australia defeated the 10-match unbeaten India to clinch their record-extending 6th World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] It will be hosted in South Africa, Zimbabwe, and Namibia.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Namibia will still have to go through the qualification process.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] From the first World Cup in 1975 up to the 2019 World Cup, the majority of teams taking part qualified automatically.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Until the 2015 World Cup this was mostly through having Full Membership of the ICC, and for the 2019 World Cup this was mostly through ranking position in the ICC ODI Championship.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Since the second World Cup in 1979 up to the 2019 World Cup, the teams that qualified automatically were joined by a small number of others who qualified for the World Cup through the qualification process.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The first qualifying tournament being the ICC Trophy; later the process expanding with pre-qualifying tournaments.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] For the 2011 World Cup, the ICC World Cricket League replaced the past pre-qualifying processes; and the name "ICC Trophy" was changed to "ICC Men's Cricket World Cup Qualifier".
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The World Cricket League was the qualification system provided to allow the Associate and Affiliate members of the ICC more opportunities to qualify.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The number of teams qualifying varied throughout the years.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] From the 2023 World Cup onwards, only the host nation(s) will qualify automatically.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] All countries will participate in a series of leagues to determine qualification, with automatic promotion and relegation between divisions from one World Cup cycle to the next.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The format of the Cricket World Cup has changed greatly over the course of its history.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Each of the first four tournaments was played by eight teams, divided into two groups of four.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The competition consisted of two stages, a group stage and a knock-out stage.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The four teams in each group played each other in the round-robin group stage, with the top two teams in each group progressing to the semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The winners of the semi-finals played against each other in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] With South Africa returning in the fifth tournament in 1992 as a result of the end of the apartheid boycott, nine teams played each other once in the group phase, and the top four teams progressed to the semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The tournament was further expanded in 1996, with two groups of six teams.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The top four teams from each group progressed to quarter-finals and semi-finals.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] A distinct format was used for the 1999 and 2003 World Cups.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The teams were split into two pools, with the top three teams in each pool advancing to the *Super 6*.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The *Super 6* teams played the three other teams that advanced from the other group.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] As they advanced, the teams carried their points forward from previous matches against other teams advancing alongside them, giving them an incentive to perform well in the group stages.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The top four teams from the *Super 6* stage progressed to the semi-finals, with the winners playing in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The format used in the 2007 World Cup involved 16 teams allocated into four groups of four.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Within each group, the teams played each other in a round-robin format.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Teams earned points for wins and half-points for ties.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group moved forward to the *Super 8* round.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The *Super 8* teams played the other six teams that progressed from the different groups.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Teams earned points in the same way as the group stage, but carried their points forward from previous matches against the other teams who qualified from the same group to the *Super 8* stage.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The top four teams from the *Super 8* round advanced to the semi-finals, and the winners of the semi-finals played in the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The format used in the 2011 and 2015 World Cups featured two groups of seven teams, each playing in a round-robin format.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The top four teams from each group proceeded to the knock out stage consisting of quarter-finals, semi-finals and ultimately the final.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In the 2019 and 2023 editions of the tournament, the number of teams participating dropped to 10.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Each team is scheduled to play against each other once in a round robin format, before entering the semifinals, a similar format to the 1992 World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 2027 and 2031 World Cups will have 14 teams, with the format same as the 2003 edition.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The ICC Cricket World Cup Trophy is presented to the winners of the World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The current trophy was created for the 1999 championships, and was the first permanent prize in the tournament's history.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Prior to this, different trophies were made for each World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Before introducing the permanent ICC Cricket World Cup Trophy in 1999, individual trophies were designed and awarded for each edition of the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] For example, the Prudential Cup trophies were used for the first three editions (1975, 1979, and 1983) when Prudential plc was the sponsor.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Similarly, subsequent tournaments used different designs until the permanent trophy was introduced.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] This shift to a permanent design was intended to establish a consistent and iconic representation of the World Cup's legacy.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The trophy was designed and produced in London by a team of craftsmen from Garrard & Co over a period of two months.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The current trophy is made from silver and gilt, and features a golden globe held up by three silver columns.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The columns, shaped as stumps and bails, represent the three fundamental aspects of cricket: batting, bowling and fielding, while the globe characterises a cricket ball.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The seam is tilted to symbolize the axial tilt of the Earth.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] It stands 60 centimetres (24 in) high and weighs approximately 11 kilograms (24 lb).
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The names of the previous winners are engraved on the base of the trophy, with space for a total of twenty inscriptions.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] A replica differing only in the inscriptions is permanently awarded to the winning team.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The tournament is one of the world's most-viewed sporting events, and successive tournaments have generated increasing media attention as One-Day International cricket has become more established.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 2011 Cricket World Cup was televised in over 200 countries to over 2.2 billion viewers.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Television rights, mainly for the 2011 and 2015 World Cup, were sold for over US$1.1 billion, and sponsorship rights were sold for a further US$500 million.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The ICC claimed a total of 1.6 billion viewers for the 2019 World Cup as well as 4.6 billion views of digital video of the tournament.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The most-watched match of the tournament was the group game between India and Pakistan, which was watched by more than 300 million people live.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The International Cricket Council's executive committee votes for the hosts of the tournament after examining the bids made by the nations keen to hold a Cricket World Cup.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] England hosted the first three competitions.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The ICC decided that England should host the first tournament because it was ready to devote the resources required to organising the inaugural event.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India volunteered to host the third Cricket World Cup, but most ICC members preferred England as the longer period of daylight in England in June meant that a match could be completed in one day.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The 1987 Cricket World Cup was held in India and Pakistan, the first hosted outside England.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Many of the tournaments have been jointly hosted by nations from the same geographical region, such as South Asia in 1987, 1996 and 2011, Australasia (in Australia and New Zealand) in 1992 and 2015, Southern Africa in 2003 and West Indies in 2007.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In November 2021, ICC published the name of the hosts for ICC events to be played between 2024 and 2031 cycle.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The hosts for the 50-over World Cup along with T20 World Cup and Champions Trophy were selected through a competitive bidding process.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] South Africa was the sole designated main host, but matches were also played in Zimbabwe and Kenya.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Eight member countries of the West Indies Cricket Federation hosted matches – Antigua and Barbuda, Barbados, Grenada, Guyana, Jamaica, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Saint Lucia, and Trinidad and Tobago.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Map showing countries' best results in Cricket World Cup (1975 – 2023).
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Twenty nations have qualified for the Cricket World Cup at least once.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Six teams have competed in every tournament, five of which have won the title.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The West Indies won the first two tournaments, Australia has won six, India has won two, while Pakistan, Sri Lanka and England have each won once.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The West Indies (1975 and 1979) and Australia (1999, 2003 and 2007) are the only teams to have won consecutive titles.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] New Zealand has yet to win the World Cup, but has been runners-up two times (2015 and 2019).
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] The best result by a non-Test playing nation is the semi-final appearance by Kenya in the 2003 tournament; while the best result by a non-Test playing team on their debut is the Super 8 (second round) by Ireland in 2007.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Sri Lanka, as a co-host of the 1996 World Cup, was the first host to win the tournament, though the final was held in Pakistan.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] India won in 2011 as host and was the first team to win a final played in their own country.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia and England repeated the feat in 2015 and 2019 respectively.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Other than this, England in 1979 and India in 2023 made it to the final which was hosted by their country.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Other countries which have achieved or equalled their best World Cup results while co-hosting the tournament are Sri Lanka and New Zealand as finalists in 2011 and 2015 respectively, Zimbabwe who reached the Super Six in 2003, and Kenya as semi-finalists in 2003.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] In 1987, co-hosts India and Pakistan both reached the semi-finals, but were eliminated by England and Australia respectively.
[src:cricket-world-cup/cricket-world-cup] Australia in 1992, England in 1999, South Africa in 2003, and Bangladesh in 2011 have been host teams that were eliminated in the first round.
